Title: I’d give it 5 stars...but
Review: Here’s what I like:This sucker will pump a lot material in short order.  During my springtime “weed blitzkreig” it cut my spray time in half.  I spray 50 gallons in my yard a year.  It’s a time saver.The high pressure setting makes for a much finer mist than my existing backpack sprayer.  The bonus is that my beer doesn’t go flat while pumping the snot out of a manual pump.  This will save me $20 a year in thrown out, flat beer.It’s also nice having my left hand free to do whatever: I.E. talk on the phone, eat Girl Scout cookies...or whatever.I like how I can buy separate tanks for for the various stuff I spray.  I no longer have to worry about getting my existing sprayer squeaky clean, or having to use multiple sprayers.Battery life is excellent.  I used an HD12.0 battery with 3 bars on the charge guage.  After 12 gallons of material, it still had 3 bars.It uses the same Milwaukee fuel batteries that the rest of my tools do (and I have a lot of them).  This is a big plus.What I don’t like:This sprayer won’t use all of the liquid in the tank.  There’s always some left in there.  If you do some Elvis Presley hip moves followed by the Macarena, it will help.  Just do it where your neighbors can’t see you.  Leaning back and to the left helps suck some additional material out, but no matter what I did, there was always a quart or two left in the tank that couldn’t be pumped out.  I thought about trying some Shakira moves, but I’m too old for that stuff.Your best bet is having a clean and labeled gallon jug to pour the leftover material into, and save it for the next time.  The “drain valve” sucks.  I had the best luck pouring out the excess material through the top, and using a funnel placed inside a gallon jug.Hopefully Milwaukee will come out with a tank that fixes this problem. This is the only real bad part of this tool.This sucker is expensive.  If you don’t spray much, it’s a waste of money unless you are trying to collect every fuel tool known to man.  He who dies with the most tools....wins!This baby is heavy.  It’s easily 10 pounds heavier than my existing sprayer.  Throw 4 gallons in it, and you will be lugging 40 plus pounds around on your back.  It’s not a huge problem if you have a good back.  The straps are wide, and it is very comfortable to wear.Make sure you keep the tank clean and don’t let any product spill when you are refilling it.  There are electrical contacts on the tank and on the base.  Some of the stuff we spray is caustic and will corrode most metals.  Keep the electrical contacts clean and dry.All in all, I think it is a good buy (not a great buy).  I don’t feel any remorse and I will happily keep using it.
Date: Reviewed in the United States on February 24, 2020

Title: Don’t buy this product

Shuts down.I took it to the services center and Milwaukee didn’t want to pay for shipping because this is a sprayer and might have harmful chemicals.Had to argue with the services center to get them to keep it to look at it.Still haven’t gotten it back yet. Trigger wasn’t sending the message to the pump overall disappointed and would like a replacement unit for another try. When it worked it worked great. Title: 3 gallon not 4 gallon sprayer

You can dance around to try and get it to work or I found turning the pressure all the way down for the last gallon helps but in the end you shouldn’t have to do this for how much this thing costs. The only reason I kept it was the convenience of being able to use my Milwaukee tool batteries. Milwaukee fix the issue!
Date: Reviewed in the United States on April 30, 2020

Title: New. Defective tank out of box but no warranty!
Review: Sold as new and appeared new in package. Leaked directly through tank bottom through obvious manufacturing defect in plastic. Not detectable until partially filled. See pic. Not usable.  Can’t have poison running down my back.  (Have come to learn same problem with units all about nation.)Though new Milwaukee would not warranty insisting NO Amazon dealer is an authorized vendor.  I had presented to Dallas Milwaukee Service Ctr well within warranty period and discussed with all three front personnel inc manager w my recpt in hand.  They sent me away without recourse.I really did appreciate Vera Tools, w some delay, backing their sale by accepting return even after 1 mo from sale. I really had NO OPTION left. Vera authorized full refund.Seems that Milwaukee may be running two sale channels, ie 'authorized' and all the rest! Buyer beware!  Seller seemed totally in dark by Milwaukee's position.So 1 star for product with really poor quality control but 5 for seller backing their sale.
Date: Reviewed in the United States on July 29, 2021

Title: 2 separate orders, same exact issue
Review: We originally placed an order for this tool the first week of April.  The day after we received it we opened the box and took the plastic covering off to fill the tank up with water.  Immediately water began to pour out of the bottom of the tank due to a large crack where the black plastic support is screwed into the bottom.  This plastic is quite thick so to see a crack that long seemed unusual.  We filed for a replacement and waited 5 more days for that delivery only to open this one the day we received it, unwrap it and go to fill it up with water and discover THE SAME EXACT ISSUE of a large crack in the bottom of the tank of the second tool.  This makes me question where the seller is getting their product.  Do better and inspect your products before sending them out to your buyers.  This has been absolutely ridiculous.

Title: great idea but one major flaw in the program
Review: We do vineyard work, gardening and forestry so this looks like a great idea for versatility and efficiency, plus if you have more of the tools with batteries that helps too.We kept mixing common farm chemicals and fertilizers and the units just kept stopping to pump.The problem is that in the manual it nowhere shows anything about how to remove the screen on the pump intake, and anybody who does spraying knows this is one of the most important operational features.The screen is inside the tank and needs to be twisted to unseat it for cleaning which may be very often because it is too tight for the pump intake and plugs easily.When you call to find out what the problem is you get argued with that you are using the wrong materials.So please rewrite the manual with this very essential information.

The tech tried to tell me if I did not buy it from an authorized retailer they would not honor warranty even if I had a valid sales receipt.I got the upset and threatened to Sue so they took it in for service.
